# Proposed fix

## Root Cause:

  In OlrNetworkClient.readNextEventWithStartScnSkip():
```java
  while (skipToStartScn) {
      event = readNextEvent();
      if (event.getScn().compareTo(startScn) < 0) {
          // Event skipped but NOT confirmed - OLR keeps it in queue
          continue;
      }
      skipToStartScn = false;
  }
```
  Skipped events are never confirmed to OLR, so it retains them in its internal queue. Once the queue reaches its limit (default ~60k events), OLR stops sending new data.

##  Proposed Fix:

  Confirm skipped events using their checkpoint SCN and index:
```java
  while (skipToStartScn) {
      event = readNextEvent();
      if (event.getScn().compareTo(startScn) < 0) {
          // Confirm skipped event to advance OLR position
          this.confirm(event.getCheckpointScn(), event.getCheckpointIndex());
          continue;
      }
      skipToStartScn = false;
  }
```



#  Additional Context:

  This problem is a combination of behaviors:
  - OLR may send old records (don't know why) when restarted from a checkpoint (up to ~100k SCN before requested)
  - OLR requires confirmation to send the next batch of events
  - The connector's skip logic confirms events but may not handle the batch boundary correctly

  The Debezium Oracle connector should be resilient to OLR sending older records and should not get stuck in an skip loop.

