**What behavior do you expect?**

`RowIdCodec.decode(RowIdCodec.encode(rowId))` must return the original 18-character ROWID
string unchanged. Any ROWID emitted in `source.row_id` of a change event must exactly match
the string returned by Oracle for the originating row.

---

**What behavior do you see?**

<img width="1329" height="613" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f1c086a4-a612-4b3d-83c6-4ac0c7e85329" />


`RowIdCodec.encode()` packs the 18-character ROWID into a 64-bit `long` using successive
6-bit left-shifts. An Oracle ROWID encodes **108 bits** (18 chars × 6 bits). The top **44 bits**
overflow and are silently discarded. When `decode()` later reconstructs the string from the
truncated `long`, those 44 bits are treated as zero, mapping every affected character to `'A'`
(index 0 in the base-64 lookup table).

**Concrete example:**

```
Input ROWID:   "AAASJqAANAAAAnkAAI"
After encode:  <lower 64 bits only — chars at indices 3, 4, 5 are lost>
After decode:  "AAAAAAAANAAAAnkAAI"   ← data loss
```

Characters `'S'` (index 3), `'J'` (index 4), and `'q'` (index 5) are silently replaced with `'A'`.

**Why exactly 7 full characters plus 2 bits:**

44 discarded bits = 7 × 6 + 2. Indices 0–6 are entirely above bit 63 and are completely
zeroed. Index 7 (the 8th character) straddles the boundary: its lower 4 bits survive, but
its upper 2 bits are zeroed — corrupting it whenever its value is ≥ 16.

| Character index | Bit positions | Fate |
|---|---|---|
| 0 | 102–107 | **Completely lost** |
| 1 | 96–101 | **Completely lost** |
| 2 | 90–95 | **Completely lost** |
| 3 | 84–89 | **Completely lost** |
| 4 | 78–83 | **Completely lost** |
| 5 | 72–77 | **Completely lost** |
| 6 | 66–71 | **Completely lost** |
| 7 (8th char) | 60–65 | **Partially lost** — upper 2 bits zeroed |
| 8–17 | 0–59 | Preserved |

The corrupted string is serialised into `source.row_id` of every Oracle CDC event. Rows
affected are any where the ROWID has a non-zero value at characters 0–6 — which is the
common case for any non-trivially large tablespace.


---

**Do you see the same behaviour using the latest released Debezium version?**

Yes — reproduced on **3.5.2.Final**. The same implementation is present in `main` and in
**3.6.0.Final** (code-inspected; not runtime-tested on 3.6.0.Final).


---

**Do you have the connector logs, ideally from start till finish?**

No log is attached because the bug produces **no exception and no warning**. `encode()` silently
discards the overflow bits and returns a valid-looking `long`; `decode()` silently reconstructs
the wrong string. The output appears well-formed — only a round-trip assertion reveals the
corruption.


