```java
final Set<String> undeliveredToastableColumns = new HashSet<>(schema.getToastableColumnsForTableId(table.id()));
for (ReplicationMessage.Column column : columns) {
    // DBZ-298 Quoted column names will be sent like that in messages, but stored unquoted in the column names
    final String columnName = Strings.unquoteIdentifierPart(column.getName());
    undeliveredToastableColumns.remove(columnName);

    int position = getPosition(columnName, table, values);
    ...
}
```

`undeliveredToastableColumns` is only ever written to — it is created and then has `remove(...)` called on it inside the loop, but its contents are never read anywhere afterwards. The `remove(...)` return value is discarded, and the set is a defensive copy so removing entries has no effect on the source list either.

## Root cause

This is leftover bookkeeping from the wal2json removal. Commit `d299c9e707` ([DBZ-4156](https://issues.redhat.com/browse/DBZ-4156), "Remove wal2json support") deleted the *only* consumer of this set — a `if (unchangedToastColumnMarkerMissing) { for (String columnName : undeliveredToastableColumns) { ... } }` block that filled in missing toasted values for the wal2json decoder — but left the set's declaration and the per-column `remove(...)` call behind.

## Proposed change

Remove the dead `Set` declaration and the `remove(...)` call (and the now-unused `HashSet` / `Set` imports). No behavior changes:

- the set was never read, so nothing downstream depends on it
- `schema.getToastableColumnsForTableId(...)` is a pure getter (returns a stored list or `Collections.emptyList()`), so dropping the call that only fed the discarded copy is observably inert
- `columnValues()` runs on the streaming hot path (once per INSERT/DELETE, twice per UPDATE, for every captured row), so this also avoids a per-record `HashSet` allocation and a `remove(...)` hash lookup per column — but the primary motivation is dead-code removal, not performance

